From config.h:

```
// This option causes the feed hold input to act as a safety door switch. A safety door, when triggered,
// immediately forces a feed hold and then safely de-energizes the machine. Resuming is blocked until
// the safety door is re-engaged. When it is, Grbl will re-energize the machine and then resume on the
// previous tool path, as if nothing happened.
// #define ENABLE_SAFETY_DOOR_INPUT_PIN // Default disabled. Uncomment to enable.
```

OK, but in the ISR in system.c it seems to be disabling the feed hold input pin, and enabling the safety door input pin?

```
    #ifndef ENABLE_SAFETY_DOOR_INPUT_PIN
      if (bit_istrue(pin,CONTROL_PIN_INDEX_FEED_HOLD)) {
        bit_true(sys_rt_exec_state, EXEC_FEED_HOLD);
    #else
      if (bit_istrue(pin,CONTROL_PIN_INDEX_SAFETY_DOOR)) {
        bit_true(sys_rt_exec_state, EXEC_SAFETY_DOOR);
    #endif
    }
```

It seems to me that in order to follow the documentation in config.h; it should read something like:

```
    if (bit_istrue(pin, CONTROL_PIN_INDEX_SAFETY_DOOR))
      bit_true(sys_rt_exec_state, EXEC_SAFETY_DOOR);
    
    #ifdef ENABLE_SAFETY_DOOR_INPUT_PIN
      if (bit_istrue(pin, CONTROL_PIN_INDEX_FEED_HOLD))
        bit_true(sys_rt_exec_state, EXEC_SAFETY_DOOR);
    #else
      if (bit_istrue(pin, CONTROL_PIN_INDEX_FEED_HOLD))
        bit_true(sys_rt_exec_state, EXEC_FEED_HOLD);
    #endif
```

So...
* Always do the safety door pin check.
* If ENABLE_SAFETY_DOOR_INPUT_PIN is defined, map the feed hold pin to safety door behavior.
* Otherwise map the feed hold pin to feed hold behavior.

Also; based on the documented behavior of ENABLE_SAFETY_DOOR_INPUT_PIN; it seems poorly named... perhaps it should be something like `MAP_FEED_HOLD_INPUT_TO_SAFETY_DOOR_BEHAVIOR`?

Did that make sense?

